{{Infobox person | name = Jennifer Dickson | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 17 September 1936 | birth_place = [[Piet Retief]], South Africa | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | nationality = | other_names = | occupation = Artist | years_active = | known_for = *Printmaking Techniques *Member of the [[Order of Canada]] | notable_works = }} '''Jennifer Dickson''' {{Post-nominals|unlinked=CM RA}} (born 17 September 1936) is a South African-born British photography artist. She studied at [[Goldsmiths College]] in England and [[Atelier 17]] in France. Since 1969 she has lived in Canada.
==Early life and education== Jennifer Dickson was born in [[Piet Retief]] in [[Mpumalanga]] province in South Africa on 17 September 1936. From 1954 to 1959, she sutdied painting and printmaking at the Goldsmiths College School of Art at the [[University of London]] in England. From 1960 to 1965, she was the apprentice of [[Stanley William Hayter]] at [[Atelier 17]] in Paris, France.<ref name=RA>Royal Academy of Arts: [https://www.royalacademy.org.uk/artist/43 Jennifer Dickson RA | Artist | Royal Academy of Arts], accessdate: 29/08/2014</ref> During this time, in 1962, she held her first solo exhibition in London.<ref name="canadian"/>
==Early career== After her apprenticeship, she began teaching at the [[Brighton College of Art]] in [[Brighton]], England. She put in place a graduate program in printmaking at this college, including photography.<ref name="canadian">{{Cite web |url=http://thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/jennifer-dickson/ |title=Jennifer Dickson |website=[[Historica Canada]] |access-date=8 March 2018}}.</ref>
In 1968, she moved to Jamaica to become a visiting fellow in fine and applied arts at the [[University of the West Indies]].<ref name="canadian"/>
==Career in Canada== In 1969, Dickson emigrated to Canada where she became the director of the graphics program at the [[Saidye Bronfman Centre]] in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]].<ref name="canadian"/><ref name="Jennifer Dickson">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gallery.ca/en/see/collections/artist.php?iartistid=1429|title=Jennifer Dickson|website=www.gallery.ca|access-date=2016-03-08}}</ref> Dickson was elected as a [[Royal Academician]] in 1976.<ref name="RA" /> She currently lives in [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], Canada.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dickson|first=Jennifer|title=Jennifer Dickson Biography|url=http://www.jenniferdickson.com/biography.html|publisher=Jennifer Dickson R.A.|accessdate=12 September 2015|date=September 12, 2015}}</ref> A lecturer and former faculty member at the University of Ottawa, Dickson has given many talks on the evolution of garden aesthetics and how this intersects with cultural practices.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.gallery.ca/en/see/collections/artist.php?iartistid=1429|title = Jennifer Dickson|website = www.gallery.ca|access-date = 2016-03-08}}</ref>
==Travel== Dickson has photographed natural and man-made landscapes in Canada, the US, England, Wales, France, Italy, Spain, Portugal, Turkey and Morocco.<ref name="Jennifer Dickson"/> Dickson is known for her printmaking techniques, through which she combines silkscreen, etching, aquatint, and collograph.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Art Carleton: Jennifer Dickson's "Even Though it Rains"|last=Burnett|first=Marilyn|publisher=Carleton University Press|year=1989|isbn=0-88629-083-X|location=Ottawa, Ontario, Canada|pages=129}}</ref>
==Honours== In 1995, she was made a Member of the [[Order of Canada]].{{fact|date=April 2018}}
